@phdthesis{bosch_quantum_2020,
	title = {Quantum {Algorithms} for {Linear} {Algebra} and {Optimization}},
	abstract = {Quantum computing utilizes the incomprehensible laws of quantum mechanics for performing calculations in fundamentally different ways from classical computers. Machine learning is one of the most actively researched and applied fields, and quantum computing has strong potential in providing machine learning with previously unimaginable computational power. Quantum machine learning is a symbiosis of two of the most promising fields of science and engineering. There are four fundamentally different approaches to quantum machine learning, as described in section (0.3). This thesis is focused on learning quantum data on a quantum computer (the QQ approach).

Chapter (1) introduces most relevant concepts in quantum information and computation, which are crucial for understanding the quantum polar decomposition algorithm in chapter (2) and its applications in chapter (3).

The quantum polar decomposition algorithm is a generalization of the quantum algorithm for linear systems of equations found in subsection (1.3.4), which strongly relies on quantum phase estimation in subsection (1.3.3) and the quantum Fourier transform from subsection (1.3.2).

The polar decomposition of a matrix is A = UB, where U is a unitary matrix, and B is a positive Hermitian matrix. One can use it for performing U, exp(-iBt) and exp(-iBt) in a deterministic way. The algorithm's complexity is O(kappa), where kappa is the condition number of the matrix A.

Polar decomposition has several potential applications which are discussed in more detail in chapter (3). The most interesting application is learning quantum unitary transformations from quantum input/output data, as described in section (3.1).

Learning how to perform a quantum unitary transformation from quantum data can be very useful. For example, properties of a system described by an unknown Hamiltonian H can be learned by generating a set of initial quantum states and allowing them to dynamically evolve within the system for a fixed time t. The input/output pairs can then be used as input for learning the transformation U=exp(-iH/hbar) generated by the Hamiltonian.},
